Kelly and Gallego

Ah, the swirling ocean of code that shows up in the wake of a popular, free, and open-source project like R. So many people write so many packages for so many things. There are packages for analyzing baseball data, for example, or tennis data, for that matter. Calculating carbonate chemistry, waveform analysis, organizing musical chord charts, exploring census data, and surely a thousand other things.

But making beautiful plots is something that R does well, and Hadley Wickhams package ggplot2 is probably the best out there for doing it. Youre already aware that this package exists, but today were going to take it for a spin.

Theres a whole theory of graphics underlying ggplot2, and you can learn a lot more about it here. But lets start with the helpfile for the package.

library(ggplot2)

?ggplot

The most confusing thing about ggplot2 is that it doesnt use exactly the same syntax as the rest of R, for reasons that we wont go into (and that I dont really understand).

Essentially, though, you use it to first create a canvas ggplot(), and then you add elements to that canvas, piecemeal. You use the + symbol to tell the package that you are adding another element to the plot.

ggplot()  #just gives you the canvas

ggplot(data = mpg,   #here, we're using a built-in dataset featuring info on different cars
  aes(x = displ, y = hwy , color = class) #the "aes" argument adds aesthetic properties to your plot. You always need this to tell ggplot what you'd like to be plotting. 
  )

OK so now weve told the package what we would like to plot (that is, what dataframe the data are coming from (mpg), the x and y variables, and that we want to vary the plot by color according to the class of the car being described.) But why is nothing plotted?

Because ggplot2 is very needy. You actually need to tell it you want to plot POINTS, in this case. You do this with another layer of the graphic, called a geom (which is just basically the kind of plot you want scatterplot, barplot, etc)

ggplot(data = mpg,   
  aes(x = displ, y = hwy , color = class) 
  ) +  #same code as above, but now with...
  geom_point()  #to tell ggplot that you want to plot points

Now, isnt that nice? And in fact, we can make lots of different plots using similar code.

baseinfo <- ggplot(data = mpg,   
  aes(x = displ, y = hwy , color = class) 
  )  #I'll save all of this as an object called "baseinfo", for ease of typing...

baseinfo + geom_smooth()  #for example, to plot smoothed lines and some semblance of confidence intervals showing the trends of each of the classes of cars

baseinfo + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm") #or, for example, to plot both the points and a linear model for each grouping

We add things like titles and text and axis labels to the plot in the same way.

baseinfo + geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Some Car Stuff") + labs(x = "Engine Displacement", y = "Highway Miles-per-Gallon") +
  annotate("text", x = 6, y = 40, label ="This is nice, no?", color = "white") +
  theme_dark() + #one of several pre-set themes; you can change everything about the plot, such as the background color, which I'm doing here
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey"), 
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "grey70"))

So you can see the appeal. Once you get the hang of it, you can make all kinds of very nice plots.

Some further examples:

ggplot(mpg, aes(class, hwy, fill=class)) +
  geom_boxplot()  #Boxplot

ggplot(mpg, aes(hwy, fill=class)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, position = "dodge")  #Side-by-side histogram

ggplot(mpg, aes(hwy, fill=class)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5)  #stacked histogram

ggplot(mpg, aes(hwy, fill=class)) +
  geom_density()  #density plot

Facets

And perhaps the most useful thing about ggplot you can create subplots for different subsets of your data. Which is very often something you want to do. Those subplots are, for some reason, called facets.

Note how convenient this is: you dont have to split your data into subsets, because ggplot does it for you.

ggplot(mpg, aes(hwy)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) +
  facet_wrap(~class)

#and you can even facet_wrap by multiple variables:

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ cyl + class)

#facet_grid is a similar idea
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, cty)) + geom_point() +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)
